Title: 12) Host Response                                                                                                                     9.961      12.841        18.210
Description: Host Response provides the Chemical and Biological Defense Program (CBDP) with robust core capabilities to
characterize the effects from exposure to chemical and biological (CB) threat agents using operationally relevant exposure
scenarios, exposure routes, methods, and models. These capabilities and the critical data products generated support medical
and physical countermeasure development, diagnostics, health effects models, and operational decision making.

FY 2026 Plans:
- Continue studies to address host response areas for traditional CB agents that earlier gap analyses have identified with
methodologies that are also directly applicable to any emerging CB threat.
- Continue to implement improvements and upgrades for artificial intelligence/machine learning (AI/ML) based prediction of
physical and toxicological properties as one key new tool and continue to assess the body’s response to mixed agents and any
novel/emerging threats.
- Incorporate AI/ML predictions to refine in vitro and in vivo toxicological assessment to select experimentation most likely to yield
actionable results.
FY 2027 Plans:
- Maintain and expand core host response characterization capabilities, predictive/in silico tools, and technologies for CB agent
characterization, both computer-based as well as in living tissues – emphasizing the use of organ-on-a-chip technologies when
possible.
- Continue empirical studies addressing host response gaps for traditional and advanced CB agents identified by gap analyses.
Maintain and expand characterization capabilities and expertise by tackling traditional gaps increasing capacity and pre-
positioning expertise to any emerging CB threat.
-Continue refinement of human effects estimates for additional CB agents providing high fidelity data to protect the warfighter
against CB threat exposure.
-Maintain and expand upgrades for computer-based prediction of physical and toxicological properties for chemical compounds
and continue to assess the host responses to mixed agents and novel/emerging threats.
