                                                                                  Congressional Adds Subtotals               -       4.000$$, $$$$, $$Chemical Biological Radiological Nuclear Advance Defense Enabling Network and Clinical Capability (CADENCC)

 CADENCC integrates clinical trial protocol designs and digital health technologies to create more efficient clinical trials, serving as a Medical Architecture Accelerator,
 for the testing of MCMs developed to protect and/or treat the warfighter. CADENCC will develop disease agnostic Master Protocols based on syndromes associated
 with priority threats, provide access to clinical network/sites for accelerated enrollment, supplement the clinical safety database for up to four RAPID Tier 3 products to
 ensure products are available for potential emergency use mechanisms, integrate technologies to create more efficient clinical trials, and leverage partnerships and pre-
 positioned assets instead of building out and maintaining new infrastructure.

 Chemical Biological Incident Preparedness and Response - Model Development (CBIPR-MODEL)

 The Chemical Biological Incident Preparedness and Response - Model Development (CBIPR-MODEL) program acquisition strategy will use a modular approach to
 supply essential non-clinical testing articles for program non-clinical studies in time of need. It will establish vendor relationships and prevent negative impacts to Science
 and Technology (S&T) and Advanced Development program cost and schedules by securing and on-shoring supply chain needs. CBIPR-MODEL will leverage S&T
 transitions and industry to conduct advanced development and evaluation of alternative non-clinical models to reduce reliance on traditional non-clinical models in
 support of medical countermeasure development.

 Chemical Biological Radiological Nuclear Defense Experimentation (CBRNDEX)

 The CBRNDEX program will use a variety of acquisition approaches to rapidly assess how integrated technologies address warfighter priorities and operational needs
 and build solution pathways to field prototype capability sets in less time. The program will use existing Multiple Award Indefinite Delivery Indefinite Quantify Task
 Order Contracts, Military Interdepartmental Purchase Request (MIPR), and Federally Funded Research and Development Centers that allow for the rapid integration of
 innovative solutions to enhance military effectiveness and responsiveness to emerging threats.

 Chemical Biological Radiological and Nuclear Defense Forward Element Experimentation and Prototyping (CBRND FE EXPP)

 The CBRND FE EXPP program will use existing Multiple Award Indefinite Delivery Indefinite Quantity Task Order Contracts, Military Interdepartmental Purchase
 Request (MIPR), and Federally Funded Research and Development Centers to conduct experimentation forward in theater and support follow-on execution.
 Experimentation efforts will identify Programs of Record (PoRs), Science and Technology efforts, and commercial solutions to close capability gaps in priority theaters
 and use a variety of contracting vehicles to conduct testing and technical assessment and accelerate delivery of capability to the warfighter.

 Forge High Performance Computing (FHPC)

 The Forge High Performance Computing program will leverage Military Interdepartmental Purchase Request (MIPR), Interagency Agreements (IAA) with the DOE
 National Labs and other interagency partners, as well as Other Transaction Authority (OTA) agreements. This will result in high throughput testing, the development of

                                                                                  Defense Program - Dem/Val
 purpose-built tools, and data catalog requirements for AI/ML components to conduct experimentation in silico to accelerate capability development. Experimentation and
 Prototype efforts will identify follow on Programs of Record (PoRs), S&T efforts, and commercial solutions to close capability gaps.

 Integrated Early Warning Manufacturing Optimization (IEW MFRO)

 IEW MFRO Other Transaction contracts will be used to support the hardware and software modernization and maturation for manufacturing of multi-modal sensing
 capabilities at distance to include integration of outputs into common operating frameworks and mission management systems across multiple Department of War and
 other agency partner activities. This optimizes opportunities in sequence with other RDT&E efforts to accelerate capabilities to the warfighter. IEW MFRO will ensure
 technologies are transitioned to the field earlier under a consolidated and holistic approach for the CCMDs and Joint Services.

 Medical Countermeasures Manufacturing Optimization (MCM MFRO)

 MCM MFRO will increase use of computational tools and manufacturing controls to reduce the risk associated with cost per dose and time to field, as well as enhance
 FDA regulatory compliance. Additionally, MCM MFRO will leverage industrial base partnerships and buy down risks to manufacturing by prioritizing onshoring of key
 chemicals (active pharmaceutical ingredients (API) and key starting materials (KSMs)) critical to produce DoW-unique enhanced biodefense medical countermeasure
 needs.

 Rapid Response Sprint Advanced Development (RRS ADV)

 RRS ADV will leverage several advanced development programs and enablers to demonstrate the potential acceleration of medical countermeasure (MCM)
 development and fielding in the event of an emergency. RRS ADV will utilize modifications to existing contracts and agreements to enable a quick response to a
 ‘live fire’ event in FY 2028 and FY 2029. This system of systems ‘live fire’ capability test will culminate in a better understanding of the art of the possible in MCM
 development across new assets, repurposed assets and diagnostic capabilities.

 Congressional Continuous Antibody Manufacturing Twin (CONG CAMT)

 CONG CAMT advances biologics manufacturing platform capabilities through the agile implementation of artificial intelligence and machine learning processes. The
 program will train models on biologics manufacturing processes and integrate them into a fully continuous digital‑twin environment capable of both off‑ and online
 autonomous process control. To reduce or eliminate lengthy and high‑cost process development activities and strengthen supply chain resilience, the program will
 develop computational design‑for‑process approaches that constrain and standardize target manufacturing pathways. CAMT will further demonstrate predicted
 product‑to‑process matching and automated production using digital‑twin automation to validate the technical approach and inform transition to advanced MCM
 development.

