Remarks

D. Acquisition Strategy
Advanced Differential Diagnostics (ADD)

 The Advanced Differential Diagnostics (ADD) program will utilize Other Transaction Authority (OTA) project agreements to identify, competitively prototype, and mature
 commercial solutions deemed technologically viable, and evaluate them in as realistic an operational environment as possible. Successful candidate systems will
 transition to the Engineering and Manufacturing Development phase to be further developed under the OTA agreement, in order to satisfy military and U.S. Food & Drug
 Administration (FDA) regulatory requirements for subsequent production and fielding to the services. Upon FDA clearance of the first ADD capability the ADD program
 will seek a Milestone (MS) C decision. ADD will continue to spend RDT&E funding after MS C to complete development of the remaining two capabilities.

 Advanced and Emerging Threat Defense (AET DEFENSE)

 The AET DEFENSE program will use a variety of acquisition approaches to rapidly assess technologies to inform understanding of the impact of current, advanced, and
 emerging threats. The program will use existing Multiple Award Indefinite Delivery Indefinite Quantify Task Order Contracts to provide technical support to studies and
 assessments of performance against current, advanced, or emerging threats. For Program of Record (PoR) systems currently in development that will be assessed
 for performance against these threats, those PoR's existing contracts will be modified to incorporate development engineering and test support for emerging threat



