 Surveillance and Pathogen Characterization - Enhanced Biological Defense (SPCHAR-ENBD)

 SPCHAR ENBD is an investment program that leverages interagency partners and existing contracts to investigate disease progression and measure biomarkers of
 selected chemical and biological defense threat agents to inform medical defense against biological warfare threats. The tailored acquisition pathway will allow flexibility
 to counter new and emerging biothreats.

 Physiological Monitoring Sensor Suite (PM2S)

 Physiological Monitoring Sensor Suite (PM2S) will leverage a rapid acquisition strategy to develop and equip joint warfighters with wearables-based CB exposure
 software capabilities that integrate into hardware-focused decision support tools developed under the CB WEARABLES-ENBD program. These efforts will support
 advanced experimentation activities with joint warfighter to identify and address CB defense capability gaps across the services.

 Chemical and Biological Wearables (CB WEARABLES)

 Chemical and Biological WEARABLES (CB WEARABLES) will leverage a rapid acquisition strategy to develop and equip joint warfighters with wearables-based CB
 exposure software capabilities that integrate into hardware-focused decision support tools developed under the CB WEARABLES-ENBD program. These efforts will
 support advanced experimentation activities with joint warfighter to identify and address CB defense capability gaps across the services.

 Non-targeted Sequencing Identification System (NSIS)

 NSIS will employ an incremental strategy to field capability quickly, with Increment I focusing on initial hardware delivery and Increments II and III developing enhanced
 software tools.

 Increment I: The Non-targeted Sequencing Identification System (NSIS) will purchase sequencers and laptops to conduct Developmental Testing/Operational Testing
 (DT/OT). The program intends to use a multi-vendor contract vehicle to procure and field systems to the National Guard Bureau (NGB), United States Army (USA), and
 United States Navy (USN).

 Increments II and III: NSIS will fund reimbursable agencies to complete laboratory and software development activities informing future increments. Laboratory activities
 include development of procedures for sequencing complex sample types. Software activities include transitioning CBDP science and technology partner bioinformatics
 algorithms, testing the algorithms, and conducting a software release to the end users.

