INSERT INTO public.pe_narratives (pe_id, fiscal_year, mission_description, justification, accomplishments, planned_program, performance_metrics, other_program_funding, raw_text, content_hash, section_hashes, source_pdf, source_page, ingested_at) VALUES ($$0605384BP$$, 2027, $$This program element (PE) resources to research, development, test, and evaluation (RDT&E) management support as a key enabler across the Understand, Protect,
Mitigate, and Enabling Investments portfolios. Chemical and Biological Defense Program (CBDP) investments provide an integrated, layered capability to enable
Department of War (DoW) missions in a chemical and biological environment, ranging from combat operations to domestic incident prevention and response. The
Projects in this PE support sustainment and modernization of laboratory infrastructure, test capabilities, studies and analyses, Joint doctrine and training, and program
and financial management support. FY 2027 funding accelerates characterization and situational awareness of emerging biothreats and accelerates delivery of
improved protection from and mitigation of biothreats, including rapid repurposing of available therapeutics and development of new vaccines.

 Individual Projects include:

 - Laboratory Support (LS6): Operating support for sustainment and modernization efforts for surety laboratory infrastructure in order to maintain and enhance
 DoW infrastructure capabilities to counter an expanding threat space, exploit advances in technology, and develop and transition CB defense equipment and
 countermeasures to the warfighter.

 - Management Support (MS6): Management support for the DoW CBDP to allow program overview and integration of overall medical and physical programs by the
 Assistant Secretary of War for Nuclear Deterrence, Chemical, and Biological Defense, Policy and Programs (OASW(ND-CBD)), through the Deputy Assistant Secretary
 of War for CBRN Defense (DASW(CBRND)).
RDT&E Management Support$$, $$The Management Support Research, Development, Test, and Evaluation (RDT&E) Project provides management support for the Department of War (DoW) Chemical
and Biological Defense Program (CBDP). It includes program oversight and integration of overall non-chemical and biological (CB) Defense Equipment (non-CDE) and
CB Defense Equipment (CDE) programs by the Assistant Secretary of War for Nuclear Deterrence, Chemical, and Biological Defense, Policy and Programs (OASW(ND-
CBD)) and defense programs through the Deputy Assistant Secretary of War for CBRN Defense (DASW(CBRND)).

 Efforts included in this Project are:

 (1) Biological Safety Research Support (BSAT RSRCH SPT)
 (2) Biodefense Materiel Readiness Common Operating Picture (BDMR COP)
 (3) Chemical Biological Radiological and Nuclear Defense Assessments (CBRND ASSESS) - Assessments for Individual
 Protection, Diagnostics, and Medical Countermeasures
 (4) Chemical Biological Radiological Nuclear Defense Experimentation (CBRNDEX)
 (5) Executive Agent Secretariat Management (EA MGT)
 (6) Forge High Performance Computing (FHPC)
 (7) Joint Acquisition CB Knowledge System Defense Business System (JACKS DBS)
 (8) Joint Concepts, Studies, and Analysis (JCSA)
 (9) Joint Requirements Office Management (JRO MGT)
 (10) Joint Test Infrastructure Working Group (JTIWG)
 (11) Office of the Secretary of Defense Management (OSD MGT)
 (12) Program Analysis and Integration Office Management (PAIO MGT)
 (13) Workforce and Biosafety - Enhanced Biological Defense (WB-ENBD)
 (14) Congressional Biological Artificial Intelligence (CONG BIO AI)

B. Accomplishments/Planned Programs ($ in Millions)                                                                                          FY 2025           FY 2026     FY 2027
Title: 1) Biological Safety Research Support (BSAT RSRCH SPT)                                                                                    0.794             0.614       0.806
Description: The Biological Safety (BSAT) Biorisk Program Office (BBPO) supports the Department of War (DoW) Executive
Agent (EA) and EA Responsible Official (EARO) for BSAT Biosafety and Biosecurity Programs in their responsibilities for

                                                                                 Defense Program

B. Accomplishments/Planned Programs ($ in Millions)                                                                                     FY 2025    FY 2026       FY 2027
mission oversight, technical review, inspection, harmonization of biosafety and biosecurity protocols and procedures across DoW
laboratories handling BSAT. This effort supports the Scientific Gaps in Biorisk Research Program (SGBRP) to address gaps in
scientific knowledge to facilitate validation of BSAT protocols and procedures, ensuring compliance with Title 50 USC § 1527,
"Improved biosafety for handling of select agents and toxins." Closing these gaps will reduce the inherent risks associated with
BSAT research in DoW laboratories, support research and development work on priority agents, and complies with Federal BSAT
regulations (42 CFR 73, 9 CFR 121, and 7 CFR 331). Research projects, selected from an order of merit list, are funded for one
year.

The Joint Interagency Biorisk System (JIBS) is the Defense Business System used by BBPO and all DoW BSAT entities. JIBS is
a real time, web based suite of products that enables the DoW BSAT Biosafety and Biosecurity programs to achieve compliance
with regulatory requirements. JIBS meets tracking, reporting, and auditability requirements across the DoW BSAT Enterprise as
required by the Army Directive 2016-24, the 2017 National Defense Authorization Act (Title 50 1527), and DODI 5101.20E.

FY 2026 Plans:
Select gap research projects based on a new order of merit list (OML), while remaining in accordance with the Scientific Gap
Biorisk Research Program (SGBRP) Charter.
FY 2027 Plans:
Select gap research projects based on a new order of merit list, while remaining in accordance with the Scientific Gap Biorisk
Research Program (SGBRP) Charter. Continue to maintain the Joint Interagency Biorisk Program System (JIBS) (Defense BSAT
Business System).
FY 2026 to FY 2027 Increase/Decrease Statement:
Increase to continue maintenance of the Joint Interagency Biorisk Program System.
Title: 2) Biological Defense Materiel Readiness Common Operating Picture (BDMR COP)                                                        0.300       2.742          2.000
Description: The BDMR COP will increase situational awareness of biodefense readiness through a biodefense logistics
common operating picture (COP) to ensure preparedness and enable a more rapid response to biological threats. The platform
will enable the biodefense enterprise to monitor assets and acquisition programs to consolidate data streams into executive
dashboards, working level planning tools to provide material readiness status, and provide supply chain visibility and illuminations.
This situational awareness of required biodefense materiel capabilities, including medical and non-medical personal protective
equipment, will also enable leaders to track and manage the necessary capabilities to protect the Total Force and mitigate the
effects of biological incidents. This effort will enable a holistic approach to addressing supply chain risk management, resiliency
and security across the entire biological defense aperture.

                                                                                Defense Program

B. Accomplishments/Planned Programs ($ in Millions)                                                                                  FY 2025    FY 2026       FY 2027
FY 2026 Plans:
Continue management support and activities for the execution of a logistic COP to enable situational awareness across
biodefense materials to include both medical and non-medical personal protective equipment. Continue efforts to integrate with
the Department's Advancing Analytics (ADVANA) tool and build system relationships with the CBDP Joint Acquisition Biological
Knowledge System (JACKS) repository.
FY 2027 Plans:
Continue management support and activities for the execution of a logistics COP to enable situational awareness across
biodefense materials to include both medical and non-medical personal protective equipment. Initiate efforts to integrate with the
Department's ADVANA tool and build system relationships with the CBDP JACKS repository.
FY 2026 to FY 2027 Increase/Decrease Statement:
Decrease adjustment to align to planned efforts.
Title: 3) Chemical Biological Radiological and Nuclear Defense Assessments (CBRND ASSESS)                                                   -             -        9.000
Description: The Chemical and Biological Defense Program (CBDP) will execute integrated assessments of individual protection,
diagnostics, medical countermeasures, and other critical CBRND capabilities in order to baseline current capability in theater and
inform follow-on experimentation and capability development activities.

FY 2027 Plans:
CBDP will leverage assets from the CBDP Experimentation & Prototyping Foundry to perform quick-turn analysis, conduct
warfighter engagements, and execute experimentation activities in support of the biological deterrence, biological defense, and
chemical defense accelerated development campaigns.
FY 2026 to FY 2027 Increase/Decrease Statement:
Increased investment provides focused assessment and analytical effort enabling CBRND.
Title: 4) Chemical Biological Radiological Nuclear Defense Experimentation (CBRNDEX)                                                        -             -        7.499
Description: Experimentation serves as a method to identify requirements and acquisition solutions to shorten the time between
gap identification and fielding. This effort focuses integrating non-material (DOTMLPF) solutions to support the delivery of new
capability sets to the services. Outcomes from these activities will inform capabilities requirements to address challenges and
gaps, transitioning S&T, service budgeting decisions, future capability-based assessments to validate alignment of potential
solutions to address operational gaps to identify requirements, as well as rapid acquisition solutions. This investment will also
help ensure a more seamless transition from capability development to the user community.

FY 2027 Plans:

                                                                               Defense Program

B. Accomplishments/Planned Programs ($ in Millions)                                                                                 FY 2025     FY 2026      FY 2027
Initiate a series of planned and coordinated events to include wargames, exercises, modeling and simulation, experiments, and
demonstrations to explore the interdependencies between and among sets of Chemical and Biological Defense (CBD) capabilities
when integrated into warfighting concepts in the near-, mid-, and long-term operating environments.
FY 2026 to FY 2027 Increase/Decrease Statement:
