B. Accomplishments/Planned Programs ($ in Millions)                                                                                        FY 2025           FY 2026     FY 2027
Title: GCCS-J Modernization and Sustainment                                                                                                   32.632            44.474      74.329
Description: GCCS-J modernization began in FY 2026 to meet validated Joint Command and Control Mission requirements while
continuing to provide the warfighter with the functionalities expected from GCCS-J. Modernization is being accelerated in FY 2027
to deliver capability to the warfighter sooner.

                                                                                ol System Software and Digital Technology
                                                                                Pilot Programs

B. Accomplishments/Planned Programs ($ in Millions)                                                                                 FY 2025    FY 2026       FY 2027
FY 2026 Plans:
GCCS-J is continuing GCCS-J sustainment activities and beginning GCCS-J modernization. Development occurs in accordance
with Joint C2 (JC2). Mission operational priorities and the Department’s JC2 Reference Architecture.

Sustainment

Produce ongoing releases to sustain GCCS-J and continuously meet warfighter needs. Additional sustainment activities include:

• Field additional capabilities in response to validated user community requirements.
• Decompose applicable existing applications into services.
• Continue cybersecurity patching and trouble ticket fixes for operational systems.
• Continue to support, sustain, and maintain operationally fielded systems.
• Expose data and scale services to support an enterprise implementation.
• Evolve more economical hardware and software architecture without impact to the operational user or Family of Systems or
interface partners.
• Field a Non-classified Internet Protocol Router Network (NIPRNet) GCCS-J offering to allow adopting units to coordinate
humanitarian assistance and disaster relief operations with non-traditional information partners in emergencies without risking
classified data spillage.

Modernization

Conduct the following modernization activities:

• Strategic Platform Information Network Environment (SPINE): Field GCCS-J backend services in the DISA-run forward-
deployed Joint Operational Edge (JOE) and Joint Operational Edge Coalition Environment (JOE-CE) cloud nodes alongside a
third-party display system as a proof of concept in support of United States Indo-Pacific Command (USINDOPACOM) exercises.

• GCCS-J Web/GCCS-J Cloud: Expand upon the capabilities of GCCS-J as a Secret Internet Protocol Router (SIPR) web
application by increasing the breadth of services available to more closely mirror on-premises GCCS-J capabilities. Field missile
warning capabilities currently residing within GCCS-J, so they may be shared with other C2 display systems.

                                                                                 ol System Software and Digital Technology
                                                                                 Pilot Programs

B. Accomplishments/Planned Programs ($ in Millions)                                                                                     FY 2025    FY 2026       FY 2027
• Zero Trust Architecture: Adopt a Zero Trust architecture as mandated to improve system security and minimize risk of
unauthorized access exploitation.
• Core Backend Data Pipelines: Prepare for future replacement of the legacy Integrated C4I Integrated Framework (ICSF) kernel
by updating channels and data flows to improve data flow (reduce latency) for ingesting, tagging, storing, correlating, fusing,
associating, analyzing, displaying, and accessing data.
• Global Logical Data Model: Begin incremental replacement of the current data model which is the product of years of system
evolution on an as-needed basis. Implementation of a modern, standardized yet flexible data model will improve interoperability
and simplify (reduce costs of) future modernization efforts.
• Container Orchestration: Expand upon the limited containerization of software components to improve scalability, resiliency,
performance, resource utilization, security, system installation/upgrade efficiency, and other areas. Containerization will also make
future system upgrades easier as services are isolated from each other.
• Open Data Service Application Programming Interfaces (APIs): Standardize bi-directional, CJADC2-compliant data service APIs
to facilitate integration of future external data sources/recipients using open standards-based interfaces.
• IPv6 Transition: Transition to an IPv6-only operations model as mandated to run in an IPv6-only environment when IPv4 is no
longer supported.
FY 2027 Plans:
Sustainment

Produce ongoing releases to sustain all GCCS-J baselines and continuously meet warfighter needs, keeping the systems current
in accordance with JC2 Mission operational requirements, priorities, and the DoW’s JC2 Reference Architecture. Additional
sustainment activities include:

• Expand the SPINE footprint to additional Combatant Commands and increase system capabilities on-demand to support
exercises and operations.
• Continue to decompose applicable existing applications into services.
• Continue cybersecurity patching and trouble ticket fixes for operational systems.
• Continue to support, sustain, and maintain operationally fielded systems.
• Limit local deployment by fielding as much capability to the enterprise as possible.
• Continue to expose data and scale services to support enterprise implementation.
• Continue to evolve more economical hardware and software architecture without impact to the operational user or Family of
Systems or interface partners.

                                                                                ol System Software and Digital Technology
                                                                                Pilot Programs

B. Accomplishments/Planned Programs ($ in Millions)                                                                                    FY 2025    FY 2026       FY 2027
Modernization

Conduct the following modernization activities:

• Strategic Platform Information Network Environment (SPINE): Deploy capabilities redeveloped or added in the C2 Global
Logical Data Model (GLDM) in the DISA-run forward-deployed Joint Operational Edge (JOE) and Joint Operational Edge Coalition
Environment (JOE-CE) cloud nodes.
• GCCS-J Web/GCCS-J Cloud: Continue expansion of GCCS-J capabilities available via SIPRNet to more closely mirror on-
premises GCCS-J capabilities. Enable import/export of GCCS-J overlays into and out of GCCS-J Web to enable shared planning
and reduce duplicative workload. Increase the availability of granular details of track groups.
• Zero Trust Architecture: Continue adoption of any Zero Trust elements not yet incorporated into all GCCS-J baselines.
Incorporate DISA’s Enterprise Identity, Credential, and Access Management (E-ICAM) tool.
• Core Backend Data Pipelines: Continue updating channels and data flows in preparation for out-year replacement of the
legacy Integrated C4I Integrated Framework (ICSF) kernel to improve data flow (reduce latency) for ingesting, tagging, storing,
correlating, fusing, associating, analyzing, displaying, and accessing data. Implement data tagging monitoring to ensure correct
distribution of information among allies and enclaves by automating analysis of inputs.
• Global Logical Data Model: Continue incremental replacement of capabilities in the legacy data model with rebuilt or new
features using the modern, standardized yet flexible data model to improve interoperability and simplify (reduce costs of) future
modernization efforts and to expand the ability to exchange data with a vastly wider array of data sources and consumers.
• Container Orchestration: Containerize software components developed in the Command and Control (C2) Global Logical Data
Model (GLDM) to improve system performance and enable easier future system upgrades.
• Open Data Service Application Programming Interfaces (APIs): Expand use of standard bi-directional, CJADC2-compliant data
service APIs to facilitate integration of future external data sources/recipients using open standards-based interfaces.
• IPv6 Transition: Finalize development of an IPv6 operations model as mandated to run in an IPv6-only environment when IPv4 is
no longer supported.
• Joint Range Extension Applications Protocol (JREAP): Enable bilateral interface with the JREAP-C standard protocol and
message structure to extend data link communication across longer distances without signal degradation. JREAP-C makes use of
internet protocols to enable long-haul data transfer without reliance on specialized radio terminals.
• Artificial Intelligence: Begin incorporation of artificial intelligence and machine learning in C2 data analysis, correlation, and
fusion.
FY 2026 to FY 2027 Increase/Decrease Statement:

                                                                                ol System Software and Digital Technology
