interface in time for the user community (DoW, Department of Homeland Security, and the U.S. Intelligence Community) to assess
the new software’s impact on interdependent systems before completing full migration. This means GCCS-J must establish a
working MARS interface a year prior to MIDB sunset.

FY 2027 Plans:
• Leverage MARS software development kits to build software to interface with the published Application Programming Interfaces.
• Map current GCCS-J data fields taken from MIDB to analogous MARS data fields.
• Develop software to accommodate MARS data fields that do not exist in MIDB.
• Establish and test initial connectivity with MARS to allow the receipt of data into GCCS-J.
• Establish a write capability from GCCS-J back into MARS.
• Field a version of GCCS-J software that will allow the user community to access the richer MARS data
