A. Mission Description and Budget Item Justification
The Global Command and Control System-Joint (GCCS-J) is the designated joint Command and Control (C2) system that provides a near-real-time, integrated picture
of the battlespace, which is essential for situational awareness in warfighting scenarios. GCCS-J is a crucial tool for decision-makers at the strategic national, strategic
theater, and operational levels. GCCS-J supports both joint and multinational operations across various networks by displaying air, maritime, ground, space, and cyber
tracks. GCCS-J also includes applications for missile warning, intelligence, targeting, and imagery exploitation.

 GCCS-J is a key component of the Combined Joint All Domain Command and Control (CJADC2) framework. CJADC2 is a modernized approach to military decision-
 making that emphasizes information sharing across all service branches to achieve agile and resilient C2. This integration allows for the connection of distributed
 sensors, intelligence, and data from all services to provide decision-makers with information at the speed of the mission.

 Key features of GCCS-J include:
 • Common Operational Picture: Provides a comprehensive view of U.S., coalition, and enemy forces across all domains (ground, air, maritime, cyber, and space).
 • Tactical Decision Aids: Offers various applications to manage the Common Operational Picture and enhance situational awareness.
 • Theater Missile Warning: Serves as the system of record for real-time missile event alerts and displays, including launch points, missile locations, threat fans, and
 projected impact points.
 • Intelligence Support: Delivers national and tactical intelligence data to C2 operators from sources like the Defense Intelligence Agency’s (DIA)'s Military Intelligence
 Integrated Database (MIDB) as well as still and motion imagery.

 Originally built in 1996, GCCS-J needs significant modernization. GCCS-J takes in sensor and data feeds from 45+ other Department of War (DoW) and non-DoW
 systems and fuses them into a Common Operational Picture to share with more than 35 consuming systems used by the DoW, Department of State, Department of
 Homeland Security, and allied mission partners. In addition to producing the Common Operational Picture, GCCS-J is part of many systems of systems fielded by
 the U.S. Military Services, including the U.S. Coast Guard, and the U.S Intelligence community. Modifying the functionality of GCCS-J can impact all the systems that
 contain GCCS-J.

 Since 1996, the C2 landscape has shifted dramatically, and the amount of data available to the warfighter from sensors, Unmanned Arial Vehicles (UAVs), and satellite
 feeds has grown exponentially. Further, the informational advantage offered by artificial intelligence, automation, and cloud computing has evolved beyond the scope of
 the original architecture. Developed on a small scale relevant to the 1990s, the GCCS-J architecture is incapable of efficiently interfacing with an increasing diversity of
 contributing and receiving operational systems. To be able to meet the growing demands and dependencies, GCCS-J must be modernized to eliminate legacy system
 components that prevent the delivery and analysis of data in near-real-time for success in contested battlespace.


