Software and Digital Technology Pilot Programs                                     lot Programs
 However, the Department has pursued a strategy of ongoing incremental modernization, canceling planned full-scale replacements in 2009 and 2017 due to the
 complexity of GCCS-J’s decentralized architecture. GCCS-J’s complexity is compounded by its nature as a heterogeneous system of systems operating across a
 diverse set of national asset and multinational partner customers, requiring intricate integration of legacy software, commercial off-the-shelf hardware, and government-
 developed applications.1,000+ GCCS-J instances can be found around the world (air, land, and sea), on 30+ U.S. and Coalition networks, and in 13 active Foreign
 Military Sales cases with an additional two pending.

 In FY 2026, the Defense Information Systems Agency (DISA) began funding the modernization of GCCS-J in accordance with Joint Staff priorities. GCCS-J had not had
 a dedicated modernization fund since 2020. DISA is taking GCCS-J to the cloud, making it Zero Trust and Internet Protocol Version Six (IPv6) compliant, and creating
 web-based access on the Secret Internet Protocol Router Network (SIPRNet). DISA is also addressing its underlying data model to decrease latency and simplify future
 modernization. The goal is to provide a centralized hybrid cloud system that generates, displays, and distributes Common Tactical Picture, Common Operational Picture,
 and Common Intelligence Picture data in near-real-time to users around the world, including those operating under Denied - Disconnected, Intermittently Connected,
 Limited (D-DIL) conditions on mission partner networks.

 Given the Departmental priorities to Reestablish Deterrence and Rebuild the Military, DISA is rapidly accelerating GCCS-J modernization beginning in FY 2027. This
 entails porting the functionality of the legacy system into the modern architecture using the Global Logical Data Model for C2 systems, developing new capabilities and
 features to meet evolving requirements (IPv6, Zero Trust, cloud deployment, container orchestration, and open application platform interfaces), and divesting of functions
 no longer relevant to the mission or that are provided from other sources. DISA will roll out new features in usable increments starting in FY 2027 until the modernization
 effort is complete and the program returns to an evolutionary sustainment model.

 As part of modernization, DISA is adapting its intelligence community capabilities to keep pace with the DIA’s migration from its retiring Military Intelligence Integrated
 Database (MIDB) to the Machine-assisted Analytic Rapid-repository System (MARS). This deeply rich new intelligence system delivers data in an entirely different
 format and methodology yet remains critical to allowing decision makers to see intelligence data in context with other friendly, hostile, and neutral elements in the
 battlespace.

 Apart from GCCS-J modernization, DISA is also addressing United States Space Command (USSPACECOM) priorities for the existing GCCS-J baseline. To effectively
 and efficiently meet its current operational needs to defend the United States and its allies in and from space, USSPACECOM has determined it needs new capabilities
 to be developed and fielded starting in FY 2027. USSPACECOM requirements overlap with operational priorities the Joint Staff provided DISA following consultation with
 the user community. Addressing these Joint Staff operational priorities will benefit both USSPACECOM and the world-wide GCCS-J user community.

 DISA is developing GCCS-J capabilities in accordance with the Mission Network as a Service (MNaaS) framework, which aims to deliver a unified, secure, and agile
 Secret environment for the Combined Joint Force. GCCS-J contributes to MNaaS by providing the Combined Joint Force with a Common Operational Picture to
 coordinate complex operations.




