B. Accomplishments/Planned Programs ($ in Millions)                                                                                 FY 2025    FY 2026       FY 2027
The increase of +$29.855 million from FY 2026 to FY 2027 is required to accelerate modernization of GCCS-J to meet Joint Staff
and user community requirements. GCCS-J requires a new system architecture and data model, which will allow for development
of microservices for quicker future capability enhancements and updates, support Zero Trust principles, IPv6 compatibility, cloud
enablement, and compliance with the Department’s CJADC2 principles for enhanced interoperability and data sharing.
Title: USSPACECOM GCCS-J Upgrades                                                                                                         -              -       34.000
Description: DISA is embarking on an effort to upgrade the existing GCCS-J baseline to meet USSPACECOM priorities required
beginning in FY 2027. Reestablished in 2019, USSPACECOM has specific requirements within its operational area to effectively
and efficiently defend the United States and its allies in and from space. USSPACECOM requirements overlap with Joint Staff
operational priorities and selected items from the GCCS-J development backlog for the benefit of the entire GCCS-J user
community.

FY 2027 Plans:
• Develop functionality to track payloads launched from orbit to their final destinations.
• Increase automation of tasks for alerting and enabling operators to protect space assets from an increasingly crowded and
hazardous operating environment.
• Develop capabilities with the GCCS-J Web capability to allow USSPACECOM users anywhere to find, manipulate, and share
data with other USSPACECOM facilities seamlessly.
• Improve Cross-Domain Solution interface to ease the movement of data between security enclaves while maintaining strict rigor
and protection of sensitive data.
• Develop GCCS-J collaborative environments.
• Improve reporting and resolution of data integrity problem reports.
• Implement an ability for GCCS-J servers around the globe to take and transfer ownership of system tracks.
• Address documented problem reports from the GCCS-J backlog involving data integrity, automation, and data flows.
FY 2026 to FY 2027 Increase/Decrease Statement:
The increase of +$34.000 million from FY 2026 to FY 2027 is required to address USSPACECOM’s unique operational needs,
many of which overlap with existing Joint Staff priorities. USSPACECOM needs these capabilities as soon as feasibly possible to
protect and monitor U.S. space assets.
Title: Machine-assisted Analytic Rapid-repository System (MARS) Interface                                                                 -              -       16.000
Description: The DIA will field the Full Operational Capability of its next-generation intelligence sharing tool, MARS, in March
2026. DIA will continue to support the legacy tool, the Military Intelligence Integrated Database (MIDB) until March 2028. Since
intelligence data is a key element of the GCCS-J Common Operational Picture, the GCCS-J Program Management Office must

